        <hl1>Women, Kids and Jobs</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr Sheila Feit on Anne Martindell's graduation from Smith College at age 87, and her remark that she did not do 'anything real' until she was 50; asks what could be more 'real' than raising family (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Graduate, Age 87, Looks Ahead'' (news article, May 20):</p>
        <p>Anne Martindell, a new graduate and the oldest person ever to graduate from Smith College, delayed her early education to raise a family.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Graduate, Age 87, Looks Ahead'' (news article, May 20):</p>
        <p>Anne Martindell, a new graduate and the oldest person ever to graduate from Smith College, delayed her early education to raise a family.</p>
        <p>But in describing her later career outside the home -- ''I didn't do anything real until I was 50'' -- she sums up the dilemma for today's women.</p>
        <p>If raising a family isn't real, what is?</p>
        <p>SHEILA FEIT, M.D.  Syosset, N.Y., May 20, 2002</p>
      </block>
